            <p>Copy.<lb/></p>
            <p>New York December 14&#91;&#44;&#93; 1885<lb/></p>
            <p>D. M. Piza&#44; Esq.<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>The subject of your<lb/> letter of the 26<hi rend="sup">th</hi> ult. deserves the earnest<lb/> consideration of orthodox Israelites.<lb/> The serious objection to it in my mind is<lb/> the question of ways and means in relation<lb/> to the end sought for&#91;.&#93; At the present time<lb/> a deluge of radicalism prevails&#44; confined<lb/> to neither our religion nor our country&#44;<lb/> but widespread among creeds and commun&#45;<lb/>ities alike. I think you underestimate<lb/> in the first place the expenses of a College&#44;<lb/> such as rent or cost of buildings partic&#45;<lb/>ularly in this city&#45;&#45; cost of library&#44;<lb/> endowments or salaries of Professors of the<lb/> first rank&#8212;it would be bad policy to<lb/> have any other&#44;with many other expenses<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>In the second place you should take into<lb/> consideration the length of time necessary<lb/> to put the Institution on a firm and<lb/> permanent basis. To make an effort at<lb/> all commensurate with the evil to be<lb/> counteracted&#44; some hundreds of thousands <lb/> of dollars should be raised and even then<lb/> it would be years ere its influence could<lb/> be felt. Our congregation alone could<lb/> not with any hope of success attain this<lb/> result&#44; but I have no doubt whatever<lb/> the Shearith Israel would gladly co&#45;<lb/>operate with others in a <hi rend="underline">combined</hi> effort<lb/> that should promise a <hi rend="underline">rational hope of</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">success</hi>&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>It would be better to do nothing at<lb/> all than to begin with insufficient means<lb/>and then fail. The radical tendencies<lb/> of the times we all deplore&#44; happily such<lb/> mad periods are not permanent and<lb/> a reaction is sure to occur. The past<lb/> history of such movements <sic>aboundantly</sic> <lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>	
            <p>proves this. Would it not be better<lb/> to abide your time for a mere favor&#45;<lb/>able opportunity and meanwhile labor<lb/> to secure a concerted effort of many<lb/> congregations which alone can meet<lb/> the case. As you ask for my counsel<lb/> I freely give it however discouraging<lb/> it may seem but the attempt of one<lb/> congregation&#8212;however well disposed<lb/>&#95;&#95; to act single&#45;handed in this matter<lb/> would &#95;&#95; so it seems to me&#45;&#45; have as<lb/> little effect as a pail of water in a<lb/> sandy desert. I am dear Sir.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours very truly&#44;<lb/>
                &#40;signed&#41; 	  Jules A. Menken<lb/></p>
            </body>
